      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can tell skeptical students that while the Constitution lists specific rights, it was written to be a flexible framework, not a rigid list that ignores new threats to liberty. Judges use substantive due process to interpret the \"Due Process Clause\" as a guarantee of fundamental fairness, ensuring that the government cannot take away basic human dignity without a compelling reason. This isn't about making up laws; it's about applying the Constitution's core principles to modern realities that the framers couldn't have explicitly predicted. Ultimately, this tool prevents a stagnant system from becoming an obstacle to justice when social values evolve.",
      "source": "target",
